<TITLE> Taiwan's DPP, KMT kick off campaigning for elections </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TAIPEI, Feb 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Thousands of Taiwanese turned up on Thursday in the first major campaign events by the ruling and opposition parties ahead of presidential elections in March, in gatherings filled with music, speeches and fanfare. Ma Ying-jeou from the opposition Nationalist Party (KMT), the frontrunner of the presidential race, and Frank Hsieh from the ruling Democratic Progressive Party adopted different styles to woo voters on the day that commemorates the "228 Incident". The 228 incident came on Feb. 28, 1947 when a Taipei street dispute over the state's cigarette monopoly spread to a chain of protests against Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalist rule. As many as 20,000 people were killed in an ensuing crackdown. "There is blood splattered in our history. It is our ancestors' dream to be masters of our own land," Hsieh told thousands of supporters who waved party flags and wore bandanas. "The economy is important, but we cannot sacrifice our freedom in the expense of boosting our economy," Hsieh said. The DPP favours Taiwan independence from China and stresses Taiwan identity, while the KMT is seen as China-friendly and willing to further improve trade ties with the mainland. Hsieh faces a tough fight against Ma on March 22, especially after the Nationalist Party, or Kuomintang, won the DPP by a landslide during the legislative elections in mid-January. Hsieh and Ma registered as presidential candidates in late January. Ma, who has been sympathetic towards the families of the victims of the 228 incident, took a soft approach with a concert. "I promise that if I'm elected, I will boost the economy, create a clean government and a fair society," Ma told hundreds of supporters during the concert. "This is what the 228 incident has taught u
